Why do I keep posting on this topic? Because I, like most people, don't like it when others openly badmouth me or my actions.<br>
<br>
Is selling epic loot wrong? How else would a bard over 52 get a scale? Not everyone has the time to dedicate to a guild strong enough to take on Gore, let alone Nortlav. The subject of the &quot;casual player&quot; comes into question. Raids are time intensive, and planning your time to allocate 5 or 6 hours doesn't always coincide with set raid times. Uber guilds also like their players to be on quite a bit, and participate. So the casual player may want to buy the difficult pieces of his epic, those that WOULD take considerable time to do (I'm not familiar with bard epic in any way, but I have heard the opinion that the scale is one of the harder parts.) I personally know  ranger who bought the chaining of the PoA globe for his epic. Is this wrong? No. (Yes epics take a lot of time, but I have read posts of the lucky gamer who on his 2 hours of playing time per day has managed to complete his epic over the course of several months.)<br>
<br>
(Perhaps my previous post was confusing. When I said that I didn't intend to have the scale to sell, I meant in any foreseeable period of time, not what I already planned. In other words: I did not intend to have the scale to sell after a few days.)<br>
<br>
Anyway what's done is done, and when I can get my damn comp to work I'll be buying the plat BS necklace and plat diamond ring for the cloak quest (Anyone know if they must be enchanted?)<br>
<br>
Last thought: There seems to be two schools of thought over this matter. There are those who believe that I am total scum for even thinking about my own interests while leading the raid, and those who think tough shit, you participated of your own free will and that's that. Just as an idea for a future topic, the idea of raiding for profit should be addressed. I personally had no clue that fellow raiders would look so poorly upon this, and would like others interested in the idea of leading raids to be briefed on what is acceptable (In other words, EMarr needs a set of raid etiquette(sp?) for the leaders.)<br>
<br>
